'Sodium chromate' (Na 2CrO 4) is a yellow solid chemical
compound used as a corrosion inhibitor in the petroleum industry, a dyeing auxiliary in the textile industry, as a wood preservative, and as a diagnostic
pharmaceutical in determining red blood cell volume.

It is obtained from the reaction of sodium dichromate with sodium hydroxide. It
is hygroscopic and can form tetra-, hexa-, and decahydrates. Sodium chromate,
like other hexavalent chromium compounds, is toxic and carcinogenic.

The substance is a strong oxidant. It is soluble in water, producing a weakly basic solution.
